<strong>IN&#45;TEXT CITATION</strong>
<br>
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	Jackson, Firtko and Edenborough (2009) found that&hellip; 
	<br>
	or
	<br>
	&hellip;was therefore conclusive (Jackson, Firtko &amp; Edenborough 2009).
</blockquote>
<br>
<br>
When the author is referred to more than once in the same paragraph do not include the date in 
subsequent references, as long as the work cannot be confused with others cited.
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	In a recent study, Jackson, Firtko and Edenborough (2009) showed that&hellip; 
	Jackson, Firtko and Edenborough also found that&hellip;
</blockquote>
<br>
<br>
If you directly quote fewer than 30 words, enclose the quotation using single quotation marks and
include the page number(s).
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	Jackson, Firtko and Edenborough (2009, p. 111) suggest that &#8216;the restaurant industry is on the 
	decline&#8217;.
	<br>
	Alternatively: It was suggested that &#8216;the restaurant industry is on the decline&#8217; 
	(Jackson, Firtko &amp; Edenborough 2009, p. 111).
</blockquote>
<br>
If the quotation is greater than 30 words it should be displayed in a double&#45;spaced, indented block
(1.3cm) without quotation marks.
